  "assets": [
    {
      "assetId": "math.found.set-theory/learning_objective/1",
      "kind": "learning_objective",
      "conceptId": "math.found.set-theory",
      "title": "Learning Objective",
      "content": "A student who achieves mastery **states whether an object belongs to a given set (∈ / ∉), evaluates a set operation (union, intersection, complement) by producing the resulting set, determines whether one set is a subset of another with a correct justification, and explains why set membership is a yes/no question independent of order or repetition.**\n\nNOT: listing set elements fluently without understanding membership rules. NOT: drawing Venn diagrams without being able to answer a membership question from them. A student who asserts {3,2,1} ≠ {1,2,3} or that {1,1,2} contains two copies of 1 has NOT achieved mastery.\n\n**Observable mastery criterion:** Given two sets A and B defined by set-builder notation, the student correctly computes A∪B, A∩B, and determines whether A⊆B — and explains each result in one sentence.\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/math.found.set-theory.md",
        "startLine": 27,
        "endLine": 37
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "math.found.set-theory/misconception/MC-1",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "math.found.set-theory",
      "title": "— \"{∅} and ∅ are the same set.",
      "content": "### MC-1 — \"{∅} and ∅ are the same set.\"\n\n**Trigger signal:** MISCONCEPTION:MC-1  \n**Active in:** Any TA where student treats the empty set and a set containing the empty set as equivalent\n\n**Conflict evidence:** \"∅ has no elements — |∅| = 0. {∅} has one element — the empty set itself — |{∅}| = 1. Ask: is ∅ ∈ ∅? No. Is ∅ ∈ {∅}? Yes. Different answer → different set.\"\n\n**Bridge text:** \"Curly braces always create a new set from what is inside them. {∅} creates a set whose single member is the empty set. Just as {apple} is not the same as apple, {∅} is not the same as ∅.\"\n\n**Replacement text:** \"∅ contains nothing. {∅} contains one thing: ∅. Their cardinalities differ: |∅|=0, |{∅}|=1.\"\n\n**Discrimination pairs:**\n- IS ∅: the set you get when you take all integers greater than 5 AND less than 3 simultaneously\n- IS {∅}: the set whose only member is the empty set\n\n**S6 path:** Introduce only if explicitly surfaced by student question — do not volunteer this distinction during Protocol E until solid membership understanding is established.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-1",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-1"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/math.found.set-theory.md",
        "startLine": 3,
        "endLine": 22
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "math.found.set-theory/misconception/MC-2",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "math.found.set-theory",
      "title": "— \"Set order matters: {1,2,3} ≠ {3,2,1}.",
      "content": "### MC-2 — \"Set order matters: {1,2,3} ≠ {3,2,1}.\"\n\n**Trigger signal:** MISCONCEPTION:MC-2  \n**Active in:** DQ-2=MC-2; any roster notation task where student reorders and claims difference\n\n**Conflict evidence:** \"The set is defined by its MEMBERSHIP RULE, not by a listing sequence. The rule for {1,2,3} is: 'x belongs if and only if x is 1, 2, or 3.' The rule for {3,2,1} is identical. Same rule → same set.\"\n\n**Bridge text:** \"A set is like a guest list — it records WHO is invited. The order the names appear on the paper does not affect who is invited.\"\n\n**Replacement text:** \"Sets are equal if and only if they have exactly the same elements. Order of listing is irrelevant.\"\n\n**Discrimination pairs:**\n- Same set: {a, b, c} and {c, a, b}\n- Different sets: {1, 2} and {1, 2, 3}\n\n**S6 path:** Use physical object rearrangement in a circle. \"I moved the coins. Did any coin leave? Did any new coin arrive? Same set.\"\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-2",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-2"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/math.found.set-theory.md",
        "startLine": 22,
        "endLine": 41
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "math.found.set-theory/misconception/MC-3",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "math.found.set-theory",
      "title": "— \"A subset must be strictly smaller than the superset.",
      "content": "### MC-3 — \"A subset must be strictly smaller than the superset.\"\n\n**Trigger signal:** MISCONCEPTION:MC-3  \n**Active in:** DQ-3 — student says A⊆A is false or uncertain\n\n**Conflict evidence:** \"Check the definition: A ⊆ B iff for all x, if x ∈ A then x ∈ B. Apply to B = A: for all x, if x ∈ A then x ∈ A. This is trivially true. The definition never says A and B must be different sizes.\"\n\n**Bridge text:** \"⊆ (subset-of-or-equal-to) is defined to allow equality. ⊂ (proper subset) requires A ≠ B. Every set A satisfies A ⊆ A but NOT A ⊂ A. The difference is in the symbol.\"\n\n**Replacement text:** \"A ⊆ B asks: does A add anything to B? If A = B, the answer is no — everything in A is already in B. So A ⊆ A.\"\n\n**Discrimination pairs:**\n- IS a subset: {1,2} ⊆ {1,2,3} (yes — ⊆ and ⊂ both hold)\n- IS a subset (surprising): {1,2,3} ⊆ {1,2,3} (yes — ⊆ holds; ⊂ does not)\n- IS NOT a subset: {1,2,4} ⊆ {1,2,3} — fails because 4 ∈ A but 4 ∉ B\n\n**S6 path:** Do not lead with the formal definition. Begin with the physical analogy: \"Is every item in this box also in this box? Well, it IS the same box.\"\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-3",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-3"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/math.found.set-theory.md",
        "startLine": 41,
        "endLine": 61
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "math.found.set-theory/misconception/MC-4",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "math.found.set-theory",
      "title": "— \"Sets can contain duplicate elements.",
      "content": "### MC-4 — \"Sets can contain duplicate elements.\"\n\n**Trigger signal:** MISCONCEPTION:MC-4  \n**Active in:** DQ-2=MC-4; union operation producing duplicated elements in the result\n\n**Conflict evidence:** \"Membership is a binary property: either x ∈ A or x ∉ A. There is no concept of x being in A 'twice.' If x satisfies the membership rule, it is in. If it doesn't, it isn't. There is no third state.\"\n\n**Bridge text:** \"A set is defined by a membership RULE (a proposition about each candidate element). For any element x, the proposition 'x ∈ A' is either TRUE or FALSE. TRUE means x is in — once. The rule doesn't fire multiple times for the same element.\"\n\n**Replacement text:** \"{1, 1, 2} is the same set as {1, 2}. The repeated 1 is ignored because 1 is already in the set. Cardinality |{1,1,2}| = 2.\"\n\n**S6 path:** Use the light-switch analogy (ON/OFF for membership). Repeating the element doesn't flip the switch a second time.\n\n---\n\n**MAMR note:** MC-2 (order) and MC-4 (duplicates) can be simultaneously active. They are independent of each other — repair in detection order (FIFO). Neither is foundational for the other.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MC-4",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-4"
      ],
